      <hedline>
        <hl1>Costas Offers Added Color</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <dateline>SYDNEY, Australia, Sept. 24</dateline>
      <abstract>
        <p>NBC technicians conclude that Bob Costas, network's prime-time host of Summer Olympics, appears to have red hair because of lighting on his set and color enhancements used to transmit telecast (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Bob Costas, NBC's prime-time host, has sandy brown hair, so why was it looking red, with lovely auburn highlights? He hasn't been dipping into the henna -- or so he says -- but he heard the murmurs. Even Hannah Storm, the daytime host, asked why Costas was becoming a redhead.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Bob Costas, NBC's prime-time host, has sandy brown hair, so why was it looking red, with lovely auburn highlights? He hasn't been dipping into the henna -- or so he says -- but he heard the murmurs. Even Hannah Storm, the daytime host, asked why Costas was becoming a redhead.</p>
        <p>Within NBC's compound here, no one saw Costas's hair reddening. But technicians examined how Costas looked to viewers in his hometown of St. Louis and in New York, and concluded that it was a combination of lighting on his set and color enhancements used to transmit the prime-time telecast.</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000</p>
      </block>
